<TITLE> Khaleda now appears in court Aug 26 </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, July (bdnews24.com)  A Dhaka court Monday extended the deadline for BNP chief Khaleda Zia's appearance, in a case involving the daily Dinkal newspaper, to August 26. Khaleda was to appear before the court of metropolitan magistrate Abdullahel Baqi Monday morning, but the court extended the time. The order came after Khaleda's lawyers appealed to the court for a time extension stating that they had not got the copy of the summons on time, her lawyer Sanaullah Miah told bdnews24.com On June 12, deputy registrar Abdul Mannan of the office of the registrar of joint stock companies and firms filed the case with Dhaka chief metropolitan magistrate court accusing 13 persons, two of whom are already dead. On the day of the filing of the case, metropolitan magistrate Abdullahel Baqi issued summons against the accused persons and directed them to appear before the court. Other accused in the case are: BNP senior joint secretary general and Khaleda's elder son Tarique Rahman, former speaker Shiekh Razzak Ali, businessman Giasuddin Al Mamun, former communications minister Nazmul Huda, former member and LDP secretary general Major (retired) Abdul Mannan, former state minister for energy ABM Mosharraf Hossain, former lawmakers Ali Asgar Loby, Engineer Monzurul Ahsan Munshi, Fazlul Azim, BNP industrial affairs secretary Rokan Uddin Mollah, BNP former secretary general late Abdus Salam Talukder and late MP Nurul Amin Talukder. The case proceedings say that the accused by violating article 1994/36/1 of Company Act did not submit return of the annual financial transactions of Dinkal Publication Limited from 2000 to 2007. Meantime, security was heightened earlier Monday around Khaleda's Dhaka cantonment's Shahid Moinul Hossain road home. Khaleda's younger son Arafat Rahman Koko, his wife, their two children and some domestic aides also live in the house. bdnews24.com Senior Political Correspondent Sumon Mahmud who went there Monday morning saw policemen closely positioned around the outer wall of the house. Some policemen were also inside the boundary. Nobody was allowed to pass through the cantonment main road and Shahid Moinul Road. Military check posts were strengthened and military police were found interrogating people more than on other days. Khaleda Zia is supposed to appear before the court at around 11:00 am Monday in a case related to the registration of the Daily Dinkal Company. But the security escort vehicle had not arrived to pick her up until 10:45 am. Advocate Ahmed Azam Khan told bdnews24.com that a petition was supposed to be submitted before the court requesting that Khaleda Zia not appear in court in person. Moinul Road seemed quieter than on other days. No commoner was being allowed to pass through the road. The media was barred from going in front of Begum Zia's house. Reporters were kept outside Jahangir Gate. Khaleda Zia is not being allowed to go out of her house for security reasons. On July 10 she wanted to visit ailing music icon Sabina Yasmin, but was not allowed on the same ground. bdnews24
